lobbying_activities:
[{'general_issue_code': 'CPT', 'general_issue_code_display': 'Copyright/Patent/Trademark', 'description': "Fair Play Fair Pay Act of 2015 - H.R.1733 (114th Congress) - Amends federal copyright law to extend a sound recording copyright owner's rights to include the exclusive right to perform or authorize the performance of the recording publicly by means of any audio transmission, thereby requiring terrestrial AM/FM broadcast radio stations that play copyrighted sound recordings to pay royalties for the non-digital audio transmissions of the recordings. Requires the CRJs to establish rates that most clearly represent the rates and terms that would have been negotiated in the marketplace between a willing buyer and a willing seller. Requires proceeds for direct licenses of transmissions otherwise licensable under the statutory license to be distributed in the same manner as statutory license proceeds. Requires payment of performance royalties for sound recordings fixed before February 15, 1972, in the same manner as royalties are paid for sound recordings fixed after such date.

Supporting the Local Radio Freedom Act - H.Con.Res.17 (114th Congress) - Declares that Congress should not impose any new performance fee, tax, royalty, or other charge relating to the public performance of sound recordings on a local radio station for broadcasting sound recordings over-the-air, or on any business for such public performance of sound recordings.

Internet Radio Fairness Act - H.R.6480 (112th Congress) - Amends federal copyright law to direct the President, with advice and consent of the Senate, to appoint the three Copyright Royalty Judges (CRJs) who serve on the Copyright Royalty Board. Increases the years of legal experience and other qualifications necessary to serve as a CRJ. Amends the Digital Millennium Copyright Act with respect to the standards applied by CRJs to establish compulsory licensing royalty rates for the public performance of sound recordings by noninteractive digital audio services.", 'foreign_entity_issues': '', 'lobbyists': [{'lobbyist': {'id': 58578, 'prefix': None, 'prefix_display': None, 'first_name': 'THEODORE', 'nickname': None, 'middle_name': None, 'last_name': 'KALO', 'suffix': None, 'suffix_display': None}, 'covered_position': 'Executive Director of the musicFIRST Coalition', 'new': False}], 'government_entities': [{'id': 2, 'name': 'HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES'}, {'id': 1, 'name': 'SENATE'}]}]

lobbying_activities:
[{'general_issue_code': 'DIS', 'general_issue_code_display': 'Disaster Planning/Emergencies', 'description': "HR 1471, FEMA Disaster Assistance Reform Act of 2015. Support of provisions in the bill to improve disaster assistance for local areas.  Issues of interest to  local emergency managers such as reauthorizing the urban search and rescue program and providing additional liability protection, reauthorization of the emergency management assistance compact grants, providing a 3 year statute of limitations on recoupment of public assistance disaster grants when no fraud, improving field transition after disasters, making mitigation funding available after fire grants, and providing management costs to subgrantees.

Support for continued implementation of the Post Katrina Emergency Management Reform Act (PKEMRA) which restored FEMA's responsibility, authority and capability to coordinate the federal government's response to disasters. Concerns regarding provisions creating additional Jt. Task Forces  in  HR 3586, the Border and Maritime Coordination Improvement Act, which would under cut PKEMRA. Savings clauses were added in the House. HR 3582, DHS Management Reform Act, with similar issue pending in Senate. 

Opposition to provision in HR 2647, the Resilient Federal Forests Act of 2015 that amended the Stafford Disaster Relief Act to transfer funds from the Disaster Relief act to Departments of Interior and Department of Agriculature for fire suppression on public lands.
------
Support  for strong National Weather Service field operations which are essential to local government emergency managers. lobbying_activities:
[{'general_issue_code': 'LBR', 'general_issue_code_display': 'Labor Issues/Antitrust/Workplace', 'description': 'Rebalance for an Effective Defense Uniform and Civilian Employees Act (HR 340), (REDUCE Act) - calls for cutting nearly 115,000 civilian jobs from the Department of Defense (DoD) - 15 percent of the overall civilian workforce. NFFE opposes.
Federal Adjustment of Income Rates (FAIR) Act, (H.R. 304) - legislation to provide federal workers with a 3.8 percent pay adjustment in 2015. Connolly introduced. NFFE Supports.
Federal Adjustment of Income Rates (FAIR) Act, (S. 164) - legislation to provide federal workers with a 3.8 percent pay adjustment in 2015. Connolly introduced. NFFE Supports.
Federal Employee Tax Accountability Act of 2015 (S 303) - would provide that persons having seriously delinquent tax debts shall be ineligible for federal employment. Introduced by Sen. Pat Roberts, R-KS. NFFE Opposes
Federal Employee Accountability Act of 2015 (HR 1658) - would limit the circumstances in which official time may be used by a federal employee. NFFE Opposes
Land Management Workforce Flexibility Act (HR 1531) - Land Management Workforce Flexibility Act -m Makes an employee of a land management agency who served under a time-limited appointment in the competitive service eligible to compete for a permanent appointment in the agency if the original appointment was competitive, totaled a period of at least 24 months, and the employee's performance was at an acceptable level. Requires such an employee's appointment to a full-time position, if such a position is offered and the employee agrees to such employment, if the original position stated that there was the potential for the position to become permanent. Introduced by Rep. Connolly, Gerald E. [D-VA-11] NFFE Supports.
Federal Employees Paid Parental Leave Act (HR 532) - To provide that 4 of the 12 weeks of parental leave made available to a Federal employee shall be paid leave, and for other purposes. Introduced by Rep. Maloney, Carolyn B. [D-NY-12] NFFE Supports
Federal Employee Pension Fairness Act (HR 785) - to repeal recent increases to pension contributions. Change current 4.4% back to 0.8%. Introduced by Donna Edwards. NFFE Supports
TDY/Per Diem Reimbursement Fix (HR. 1193) - To nullify Nov.1 DoD change to reimbursement rates for civilian and military personnel on long-term TDY. Introduced by Rep. Kilmer. NFFE Supports
Government Employee Pension Reform Act of 2015 (HR 1230) - would revise the definition of average pay for the purposes of federal employee pensions under the Civil Service Retirement System and Federal Employees Retirement System from averaging base pay over any three years to the average over five years.  Introduced by Rep. Bruce Westerman (R-AR-4).  NFFE opposes.
PAID for Progress Act (HR 1137) - would reduce the rate of basic pay for any federal employee with a salary exceeding $100,000 by 8.7 percent.  Introduced by Rep. Tom Rice (R-SC-7).  NFFE opposes.
Just Google It Act (S 1636) - would repeal the National Technical Information Act of 1988 in an effort to streamline the collection and distribution of Government information.  Introduced by Sen. Mark Kirk (R-IL).
VA Accountability Act of 2015 (HR 1994) - would authorize the Department of Veterans Affairs to remove or demote a VA employee based on performance or misconduct, reducing the time for repeals and responses, and extending the VA employee probationary period.  Introduced by Rep. Jeff Miller (R-FL-1).  NFFE opposes.
Land Management Workforce Flexibility Act of 2015 (S. 1591) - would provide a pathway for temporary seasonal employees in Federal land management agencies to compete for vacant permanent positions under internal merit promotion procedures.  Introduced by Sen. Jon Tester (D-MT).  NFFE supports.
Stop Wasteful Federal Bonuses Act of 2015 (S. 742) - would prohibit federal agencies from awarding bonuses for five years to any employee to which the Inspector General makes an adverse finding.  Introduced by Sen. Kelly Ayotte (R-NH).  NFFE opposes.
Federal Firefighters Fairness Act of 2015 (HR 1035) - would create the presumption that a disability or death of a Federal employee in fire protection activities caused by any certain related disease is the result of the performance of such employees duty.  Introduce by Rep. Lois Capps (D-CA-24).  NFFE supports.
Defending Public Safety Employees Retirement Act (HR 2146) - allows Federal law enforcement officers, firefighters, and air traffic controllers to make penalty-free withdrawals from governmental pension plans after age 50.  Used as a vehicle for passage of Trade Promotion Authority.  Introduced by Rep. David Reichert (D-WA-8) and signed into law by the President on June 29, 2015.
Department of Veterans Affairs Employee Fairness Act of 2015 (S 1257) - would repeal the exclusion from the collective bargaining rights of Veterans Health Administrations employees addressing any matter or question concerning professional conduct or competence, peer review, or the establishment, determinations, or adjustment of employee compensation.  Introduced by Sen. Sherrod Brown (D-OH).  NFFE supports.
Federal Employee Tax Accountability Act of 2015 (HR. 1563) - would provide that individuals having seriously delinquent tax debts shall be ineligible for Federal employment.  Introduced by Rep. Jason Chaffetz (R-UT-3).  NFFE opposes.
Federal Employee Accountability Act of 2015 (HR 1658) - would repeal provisions authorizing a federal employee from collecting official time in negotiating a collective bargaining agreement when  that employee would otherwise be on duty.  Introduced by Rep. Jody Hice (R-GA-10).  NFFE opposes.
NTIS Elimination Act (S  787) - would repeal the National Technical Information Act of 1988 in an effort to streamline the collection and distribution of Government information.  Intoduced by Sen. Claire McCaskill (D-MO).
To Streamline the Collection and Distribution of Government Information (HR  443) - would repeal the National Technical Information Act of 1988 in an effort to streamline the collection and distribution of Government information.  Introduced by Rep. Jim Bridenstine (R-OK-1).
Locality Pay Equity Act (HR 3492) - (1) prohibits the Office of Personnel Management (OPM) from defining more than one local wage area for prevailing rate employees within a pay locality, except with respect to the pay locality designated as "Rest of United States;" and (2) requires the OPM to ensure that this Act shall not have the effect of reducing any rate of basic pay for any individual who is serving as a prevailing rate employee. Introduced by Rep. Matt Cartwright (D-PA-17)
Veterans First Act (S. 2921) - intended to bring accountability to Department of Veterans Affairs (VA), in reality outlines punitive measures that would harm rank-and-file VA employees and medical professionals and decrease quality of care given to our veterans. NFFE opposes. 
Federal Adjustment of Income Rates (H.R. 4585), (FAIR Act) -  calls for a modest but much-needed 5.3% pay adjustment for federal employees in FY2017 (4.9% pay adjustment, with a locality pay adjustment of 1.4%). NFFE supports.
Federal Adjustment of Income Rates (S. 2699), (FAIR Act) -  calls for a modest but much-needed 5.3% pay adjustment for federal employees in FY2017 (4.9% pay adjustment, with a locality pay adjustment of 1.4%). NFFE supports.
Veterans Access, Choice and Accountability Act of 2014 (H.R. 3230) - created an expedited firing process for VA Senior Executives, which Congress attempted to extend to rank-and-file VA Employees. The Merit Systems Protection Board (MSPB) questioned its constitutionality, and Department of Justice (DoJ) declared it would not defend the constitutionality of this provision. NFFE opposed. 
VA Accountability Act of 2016 (S. 2554) - Senate counterpart to H.R. 1994, calls for expedited firing process and outlines reasons for termination based on performance. NFFE opposes. 
Government Reform and Improvement Act of 2016 (H.R.4361) - aims to extend the punitive and arbitrary provisions found in the 2014 Veterans Choice Act to the federal workforce at large, violating the due process rights of federal employees. Congressman Cummings and White House have voiced opposition to this bill. NFFE opposes. 
Promote Accountability and Government Efficiency Act (H.R. 6278) - bill would universally make federal civil servants at-will employees, eliminating federal employee due process rights as we know them.
